<Layout title="Endocrine & Metabolic Assessment Tools" description="Endocrine and metabolic assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Endocrine &amp; Metabolic</div>
  <h1>Endocrine &amp; Metabolic Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Assessment tools and criteria for endocrine emergencies, diabetes risk, and metabolic disorders.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>DKA Severity Classification</strong> — Diabetic ketoacidosis staged by pH and bicarbonate: Mild (pH 7.25–7.30, HCO₃ 15–18), Moderate (pH 7.00–7.24, HCO₃ 10–14), Severe (pH &lt;7.00, HCO₃ &lt;10). Guides ICU vs. floor admission.</li>
      <li><strong>HHS Criteria (Hyperosmolar Hyperglycemic State)</strong> — Diagnostic features: glucose &gt;600 mg/dL, serum osmolality &gt;320 mOsm/kg, absence of significant acidosis (pH &gt;7.30), minimal ketonemia.</li>
      <li><strong>Burch-Wartofsky Point Scale (Thyroid Storm)</strong> — Quantifies thyroid storm likelihood: thermoregulatory dysfunction, CNS effects, GI-hepatic dysfunction, cardiovascular effects, precipitating event. Score ≥45 = thyroid storm.</li>
      <li><strong>Adrenal Crisis Recognition Parameters</strong> — Clinical and laboratory criteria for adrenal insufficiency: hypotension refractory to fluids, hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, hypoglycemia; guided by cortisol levels and clinical context.</li>
      <li><strong>FINDRISC (Finnish Diabetes Risk Score)</strong> — Eight-item type 2 diabetes risk assessment: age, BMI, waist circumference, physical activity, diet, antihypertensive medication, blood glucose history, family history. Score 0–26.</li>
      <li><strong>ADA Diabetes Risk Test</strong> — American Diabetes Association 7-item questionnaire estimating type 2 diabetes risk; accessible patient-facing tool for community screening.</li>
      <li><strong>Hypoglycemia Unawareness Assessment</strong> — Clinical evaluation of impaired awareness of hypoglycemia; Gold Score and Clarke questionnaire used to identify patients at risk for severe hypoglycemic episodes without warning symptoms.</li>
      <li><strong>Metabolic Syndrome Criteria (IDF / ATP III)</strong> — Combination of central obesity, elevated triglycerides, low HDL, elevated blood pressure, and impaired fasting glucose. IDF requires waist circumference; ATP III requires 3 of 5 criteria.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
